# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: social-choice-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] The result is often cited in discussions of voting rules, where it shows no ranked voting rule can eliminate the spoiler effect.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] This result was first shown by the Marquis de Condorcet, whose voting paradox showed the impossibility of logically-consistent majority rule; Arrow's theorem generalizes Condorcet's findings to include non-majoritarian rules like collective leadership or consensus decision-making.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] While the impossibility theorem shows all ranked voting rules must have spoilers, the frequency of spoilers differs dramatically by rule.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Plurality-rule methods like choose-one and ranked-choice (instant-runoff) voting are highly sensitive to spoilers, creating them even in some situations where they are not mathematically necessary (e.g. in center squeezes).
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] In contrast, majority-rule (Condorcet) methods of ranked voting uniquely minimize the number of spoiled elections by restricting them to voting cycles, which are rare in ideologically-driven elections.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Under some models of voter preferences (like the left-right spectrum assumed in the median voter theorem), spoilers disappear entirely for these methods.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Rated voting rules, where voters assign a separate grade to each candidate, are not affected by Arrow's theorem.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Arrow initially asserted the information provided by these systems was meaningless and therefore could not be used to prevent paradoxes, leading him to overlook them.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] However, Arrow would later describe this as a mistake, admitting rules based on cardinal utilities (such as score and approval voting) are not subject to his theorem.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] When Kenneth Arrow proved his theorem in 1950, it inaugurated the modern field of social choice theory, a branch of welfare economics studying mechanisms to aggregate preferences and beliefs across a society.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Such a mechanism of study can be a market, voting system, constitution, or even a moral or ethical framework.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] In the context of Arrow's theorem, citizens are assumed to have ordinal preferences, i.e. orderings of candidates.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] If *A* and *B* are different candidates or alternatives, then $A\succ B$ means *A* is preferred to *B*.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Individual preferences (or ballots) are required to satisfy intuitive properties of orderings, e.g. they must be transitive—if $A\succeq B$ and $B\succeq C$ , then $A\succeq C$ .
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] The social choice function is then a mathematical function that maps the individual orderings to a new ordering that represents the preferences of all of society.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Arrow's original statement of the theorem included non-negative responsiveness as a condition, i.e., that *increasing* the rank of an outcome should not make them *lose*—in other words, that a voting rule shouldn't penalize a candidate for being more popular.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] However, this assumption is not needed or used in his proof (except to derive the weaker condition of Pareto efficiency), and Arrow later corrected his statement of the theorem to remove the inclusion of this condition.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] A commonly-considered axiom of rational choice is *independence of irrelevant alternatives* (IIA), which says that when deciding between *A* and *B*, one's opinion about a third option *C* should not affect their decision.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Morgenbesser, ordering dessert, is told by a waitress that he can choose between blueberry or apple pie.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Soon the waitress comes back and explains cherry pie is also an option.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Arrow's theorem shows that if a society wishes to make decisions while always avoiding such self-contradictions, it cannot use ranked information alone.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Condorcet's example is already enough to see the impossibility of a fair ranked voting system, given stronger conditions for fairness than Arrow's theorem assumes.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] If C is chosen as the winner, it can be argued any fair voting system would say B should win instead, since two voters (1 and 2) prefer B to C and only one voter (3) prefers C to B .
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] However, by the same argument A is preferred to B , and C is preferred to A , by a margin of two to one on each occasion.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Thus, even though each individual voter has consistent preferences, the preferences of society are contradictory: A is preferred over B which is preferred over C which is preferred over A .
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Because of this example, some authors credit Condorcet with having given an intuitive argument that presents the core of Arrow's theorem.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] However, Arrow's theorem is substantially more general; it applies to methods of making decisions other than one-person-one-vote elections, such as markets or weighted voting, based on ranked ballots.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] (Completeness) At least one of $(\mathbf {a} ,\mathbf {b} )$ or $(\mathbf {b} ,\mathbf {a} )$ must be in R .
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] The element $(\mathbf {a} ,\mathbf {b} )$ being in R is interpreted to mean that alternative $\mathbf {a}$ is preferred to or indifferent to alternative $\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] This situation is often denoted $\mathbf {a} \succsim \mathbf {b}$ or $\mathbf {a} R\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] The symmetric part of R yields the indifference relation I .
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] This is written as $\mathbf {a} \sim \mathbf {b}$ or $\mathbf {a} I\mathbf {b}$ if and only if $(\mathbf {a} ,\mathbf {b} )$ and $(\mathbf {b} ,\mathbf {a} )$ are both in R .
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] The asymmetric part of R yields the (strict) preference relation P .
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] This is written as $\mathbf {a} \succ \mathbf {b}$ or $\mathbf {a} P\mathbf {b}$ if and only if $(\mathbf {a} ,\mathbf {b} )$ is in R and $(\mathbf {b} ,\mathbf {a} )$ is not in R .
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] In the following, preference of one alternative over another denotes strict preference.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Denote the set of all preferences on A by $\Pi (A)$ .
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Equivalently, $\Pi (A)$ is the set of rankings of the alternatives in A from top to bottom, with ties allowed.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] which aggregates voters' preferences into a single preference on A .
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] An N -tuple $(R_{1},\ldots ,R_{N})\in \Pi (A)^{N}$ of voters' preferences is called a *preference profile*.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Arrow's theorem establishes that no ranked voting rule can *always* satisfy independence of irrelevant alternatives, but it says nothing about the frequency of spoilers.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] This led Arrow to remark that "Most systems are not going to work badly all of the time.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Attempts at dealing with the effects of Arrow's theorem take one of two approaches: either accepting his rule and searching for the least spoiler-prone methods, or dropping one or more of his assumptions, such as by focusing on rated voting rules.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] The first set of methods studied by economists are the majority-rule, or *Condorcet*, methods.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] These rules limit spoilers to situations where majority rule is self-contradictory, called Condorcet cycles, and as a result uniquely minimize the possibility of a spoiler effect among ranked rules.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] (Indeed, many different social welfare functions can meet Arrow's conditions under such restrictions of the domain.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Unfortunately, as Condorcet proved, this rule can be intransitive on some preference profiles.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Thus, Condorcet proved a weaker form of Arrow's impossibility theorem long before Arrow, under the stronger assumption that a voting system in the two-candidate case will agree with a simple majority vote.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Unlike pluralitarian rules such as instant-runoff voting or plurality voting, Condorcet methods avoid the spoiler effect in non-cyclic elections, where candidates can be chosen by majority rule.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Political scientists have found such cycles to be fairly rare, suggesting they may be of limited practical concern.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Spatial voting models also suggest such paradoxes are likely to be infrequent or even non-existent.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Soon after Arrow published his theorem, Duncan Black showed his own remarkable result, the median voter theorem.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] The theorem proves that if voters and candidates are arranged on a left-right spectrum, Arrow's conditions are all fully compatible, and all will be met by any rule satisfying Condorcet's majority-rule principle.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] More formally, Black's theorem assumes preferences are *single-peaked*: a voter's happiness with a candidate goes up and then down as the candidate moves along some spectrum.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] For example, in a group of friends choosing a volume setting for music, each friend would likely have their own ideal volume; as the volume gets progressively too loud or too quiet, they would be increasingly dissatisfied.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] If the domain is restricted to profiles where every individual has a single-peaked preference with respect to the linear ordering, then social preferences are acyclic.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] In this situation, Condorcet methods satisfy a wide variety of highly-desirable properties, including being fully spoilerproof.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] The rule does not fully generalize from the political spectrum to the political compass, a result related to the McKelvey-Schofield chaos theorem.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] However, a well-defined Condorcet winner does exist if the distribution of voters is rotationally symmetric or otherwise has a uniquely-defined median.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] In most realistic situations, where voters' opinions follow a roughly-normal distribution or can be accurately summarized by one or two dimensions, Condorcet cycles are rare (though not unheard of).
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] The Campbell-Kelly theorem shows that Condorcet methods are the most spoiler-resistant class of ranked voting systems: whenever it is possible for some ranked voting system to avoid a spoiler effect, a Condorcet method will do so.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] In other words, replacing a ranked method with its Condorcet variant (i.e. elect a Condorcet winner if they exist, and otherwise run the method) will sometimes prevent a spoiler effect, but can never create a new one.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] In 1977, Ehud Kalai and Eitan Muller gave a full characterization of domain restrictions admitting a nondictatorial and strategyproof social welfare function.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] These correspond to preferences for which there is a Condorcet winner.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Holliday and Pacuit devised a voting system that provably minimizes the number of candidates who are capable of spoiling an election, albeit at the cost of occasionally failing vote positivity (though at a much lower rate than seen in instant-runoff voting).
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] As shown above, the proof of Arrow's theorem relies crucially on the assumption of ranked voting, and is not applicable to rated voting systems.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] These systems ask voters to rate candidates on a numerical scale (e.g. from 0–10), and then elect the candidate with the highest average (for score voting) or median (graduated majority judgment).
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] This opens up the possibility of finding another social choice procedure that satisfies independence of irrelevant alternatives.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Arrow's theorem can thus be considered a special case of Harsanyi's utilitarian theorem and other utility representation theorems like the VNM theorem, which show rational behavior requires consistent cardinal utilities.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] While Arrow's theorem does not apply to graded systems, Gibbard's theorem still does: no voting game can be straightforward (i.e. have a single, clear, always-best strategy).
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Arrow's framework assumed individual and social preferences are orderings or rankings, i.e. statements about which outcomes are better or worse than others.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Taking inspiration from the behavioralist approach, some philosophers and economists rejected the idea of comparing internal human experiences of well-being.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Arrow originally agreed with these position, rejecting the meaningfulness of cardinal utilities, thus interpreting his theorem as a kind of proof for nihilism or egoism.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] However, he later stated that cardinal methods can provide additional useful information, and that his theorem is not applicable to them.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Similarly, Amartya Sen first claimed interpersonal comparability is necessary for IIA, but later came to argue in favor of cardinal methods for assessing social choice, arguing they would only require "rather limited levels of partial comparability" to hold in practice.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Other scholars have noted that interpersonal comparisons of utility are not unique to cardinal voting, but are instead a necessity of any non-dictatorial choice procedure, with cardinal voting rules making these comparisons explicit.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] In psychometrics, there is a general consensus that self-reported ratings (e.g.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Likert scales) are meaningful and provide more information than pure rankings, as well as showing higher validity and reliability.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Likert scales) provide more information than rankings alone.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Therefore, it seems that human beings can successfully operationalize an integer scale for feelings".
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Behavioral economists have shown individual irrationality involves violations of IIA (e.g. with decoy effects), suggesting human behavior can cause IIA failures even if the voting method itself does not.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] However, past research has typically found such effects to be fairly small, and such psychological spoilers can appear regardless of electoral system.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Balinski and Laraki discuss techniques of ballot design derived from psychometrics that minimize these psychological effects, such as asking voters to give each candidate a verbal grade (e.g.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] "bad", "neutral", "good", "excellent") and issuing instructions to voters that refer to their ballots as judgments of individual candidates.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Similar techniques are often discussed in the context of contingent valuation.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] In addition to the above practical resolutions, there exist unusual (less-than-practical) situations where Arrow's requirement of IIA can be satisfied.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Supermajority rules can avoid Arrow's theorem at the cost of being poorly-decisive (i.e. frequently failing to return a result).
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] In this case, a threshold that requires a $2/3$ majority for ordering 3 outcomes, $3/4$ for 4, etc. does not produce voting paradoxes.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] In spatial (n-dimensional ideology) models of voting, this can be relaxed to require only $1-e^{-1}$ (roughly 64%) of the vote to prevent cycles, so long as the distribution of voters is well-behaved (quasiconcave).
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] These results provide some justification for the common requirement of a two-thirds majority for constitutional amendments, which is sufficient to prevent cyclic preferences in most situations.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Arrow's theorem is not related to strategic voting, which does not appear in his framework, though the theorem does have important implications for strategic voting (being used as a lemma to prove Gibbard's theorem).
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] The Arrovian framework of social welfare assumes all voter preferences are known and the only issue is in aggregating them.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Monotonicity (called positive association by Arrow) is not a condition of Arrow's theorem.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] This misconception is caused by a mistake by Arrow himself, who included the axiom in his original statement of the theorem but did not use it.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Dropping the assumption does not allow for constructing a social welfare function that meets his other conditions.
[src:social-choice-theory/arrow-s-impossibility-theorem] Contrary to a common misconception, Arrow's theorem deals with the limited class of ranked-choice voting systems, rather than voting systems as a whole.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] The usefulness of a particular voting system can be severely limited if it takes a very long time to calculate the winner of an election.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] Therefore, it is important to design fast algorithms that can evaluate a voting rule when given ballots as input.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] As is common in computational complexity theory, an algorithm is thought to be efficient if it takes polynomial time.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] Many popular voting rules can be evaluated in polynomial time in a straightforward way (i.e., counting), such as the Borda count, approval voting, or the plurality rule.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] For rules such as the Schulze method or ranked pairs, more sophisticated algorithms can be used to show polynomial runtime.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] Certain voting systems, however, are computationally difficult to evaluate.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] In particular, winner determination for the Kemeny-Young method, Dodgson's method, and Young's method are all NP-hard problems.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] This has led to the development of approximation algorithms and fixed-parameter tractable algorithms to improve the theoretical calculation of such problems.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] An important differentiation between voting rules is the format of ballots used by the voters to represent their preference.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] The two most common formats are approval ballots and ordinal ranks.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] In approval ballots, each voter approves some candidates she likes.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] There is no further differentiation or hierarchy within the approved candidates.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] The same holds for the non-approved candidates.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] Thus, such ballots are also called dichotomous.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] Approval ballots are used for instance in satisfaction approval voting and proportional approval voting.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] In contrast, ordinal ranks require the voter to rank all candidates from best to worst.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] This type of ballot is used for example in Borda's rule or in Bucklin voting.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] There are many other types of ballot formats described in literature, such as truncated ranks, trichotomous ballots, or cardinal utility ballots.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] Some research in computational social choice is focused on how representative ballot formats are, and on developing expressive, yet compact ballot formats.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] This is especially important in combinatorial settings, such as multiwinner voting.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] A tournament solution is a rule that assigns to every tournament a set of winners.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] Since a preference profile induces a tournament through its majority relation, every tournament solution can also be seen as a voting rule which only uses information about the outcomes of pairwise majority contests.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] Many tournament solutions have been proposed, and computational social choice theorists have studied the complexity of the associated winner determination problems.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] From a computational perspective, such domain restrictions are useful to speed up winner determination problems, both computationally hard single-winner and multi-winner rules can be computed in polynomial time when preferences are structured appropriately.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] On the other hand, manipulation problem also tend to be easy on these domains, so complexity shields against manipulation are less effective.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] Another computational problem associated with preference restrictions is that of recognizing when a given preference profile belongs to some restricted domain.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] This task is polynomial time solvable in many cases, including for single-peaked and single-crossing preferences, but can be hard for more general classes.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] While most traditional voting rules focus on selecting a single winner, many situations require selecting multiple winners.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] This is the case when a fixed-size parliament or a committee is to be elected, though multiwinner voting rules can also be used to select a set of recommendations or facilities or a shared bundle of items.
[src:social-choice-theory/computational-social-choice] Work in computational social choice has focused on defining such voting rules, understanding their properties, and studying the complexity of the associated winner determination problems.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] In social choice theory, **Condorcet's voting paradox** (also called **Condorcet's paradox** or the **Condorcet paradox**) is a fundamental discovery by the Marquis de Condorcet that majority rule is inherently self-contradictory.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Examples of Condorcet's paradox are called **Condorcet cycles** or **cyclic ties**.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] In such a cycle, every possible choice is rejected by the electorate in favor of another alternative, who is preferred by more than half of all voters.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Thus, any attempt to ground social decision-making in majoritarianism must accept such self-contradictions (commonly called spoiler effects).
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Systems that attempt to do so, while minimizing the rate of such self-contradictions, are called Condorcet methods.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Condorcet's paradox is a special case of Arrow's paradox, which shows that *any* kind of social decision-making process is either self-contradictory, a dictatorship, or incorporates information about the strength of different voters' preferences (e.g. cardinal utility or rated voting).
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Condorcet's paradox was first discovered by Catalan philosopher and theologian Ramon Llull in the 13th century, during his investigations into church governance, but his work was lost until the 21st century.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] The mathematician and political philosopher Marquis de Condorcet rediscovered the paradox in the late 18th century.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Condorcet's discovery means he arguably identified the key result of Arrow's impossibility theorem, albeit under stronger conditions than required by Arrow: Condorcet cycles create situations where any ranked voting system that respects majorities must have a spoiler effect.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] If C is chosen as the winner, it can be argued that B should win instead, since two voters (1 and 2) prefer B to C and only one voter (3) prefers C to B.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] However, by the same argument A is preferred to B, and C is preferred to A, by a margin of two to one on each occasion.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Thus the society's preferences show cycling: A is preferred over B which is preferred over C which is preferred over A.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] As a result, any attempt to appeal to the principle of majority rule will lead to logical self-contradiction.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Regardless of which alternative we select, we can find another alternative that would be preferred by most voters.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] The voters in Cactus County prefer the incumbent county executive **Alex** of the Farmers' Party over rival **Beatrice** of the Solar Panel Party by about a 2-to-1 margin.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] This year a third candidate, **Charlie**, is running as an independent.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Charlie is a wealthy and outspoken businessman, of whom the voters hold polarized views.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Therefore a majority of voters prefer Alex to Beatrice (A > B), as they always have.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] A majority of voters are either Beatrice-lovers or Charlie-haters, so prefer Beatrice to Charlie (B > C).
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] And a majority of voters are either Charlie-lovers or Alex-haters, so prefer Charlie to Alex (C > A).
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Combining the three preferences gives us A > B > C > A, a Condorcet cycle.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] It is possible to estimate the probability of the paradox by extrapolating from real election data, or using mathematical models of voter behavior, though the results depend strongly on which model is used.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] We can calculate the probability of seeing the paradox for the special case where voter preferences are uniformly distributed among the candidates.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] For n voters providing a preference list of three candidates A, B, C, we write $X_{n}$ (resp. $Y_{n}$ , $Z_{n}$ ) the random variable equal to the number of voters who placed A in front of B (respectively B in front of C, C in front of A).
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] The sought probability is $p_{n}=2P(X_{n}>n/2,Y_{n}>n/2,Z_{n}>n/2)$ (we double because there is also the symmetric case A> C> B> A).
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] The sequence seems to be tending towards a finite limit.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] The asymptotic probability of encountering the Condorcet paradox is therefore ${{3\arccos {1 \over 3}} \over {2\pi }}-{1 \over 2}={\arcsin {{\sqrt {6}} \over 9} \over \pi }$ which gives the value 8.77%.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Some results for the case of more than three candidates have been calculated and simulated.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] All of these models are unrealistic, but can be investigated to establish an upper bound on the likelihood of a cycle.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] When modeled with more realistic voter preferences, Condorcet paradoxes in elections with a small number of candidates and a large number of voters become very rare.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] A study of three-candidate elections analyzed 12 different models of voter behavior, and found the spatial model of voting to be the most accurate to real-world ranked-ballot election data.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Analyzing this spatial model, they found the likelihood of a cycle to decrease to zero as the number of voters increases, with likelihoods of 5% for 100 voters, 0.5% for 1000 voters, and 0.06% for 10,000 voters.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Another spatial model found likelihoods of 2% or less in all simulations of 201 voters and 5 candidates, whether two or four-dimensional, with or without correlation between dimensions, and with two different dispersions of candidates.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Many attempts have been made at finding empirical examples of the paradox.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Empirical identification of a Condorcet paradox presupposes extensive data on the decision-makers' preferences over all alternatives—something that is only very rarely available.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] While examples of the paradox seem to occur occasionally in small settings (e.g., parliaments) very few examples have been found in larger groups (e.g. electorates), although some have been identified.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] A summary of 37 individual studies, covering a total of 265 real-world elections, large and small, found 25 instances of a Condorcet paradox, for a total likelihood of 9.4% (and this may be a high estimate, since cases of the paradox are more likely to be reported on than cases without).
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] An analysis of 883 three-candidate elections extracted from 84 real-world ranked-ballot elections of the Electoral Reform Society found a Condorcet cycle likelihood of 0.7%.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] These derived elections had between 350 and 1,957 voters.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] A similar analysis of data from the 1970–2004 American National Election Studies thermometer scale surveys found a Condorcet cycle likelihood of 0.4%.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] These derived elections had between 759 and 2,521 "voters".
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Andrew Myers, who operates the Condorcet Internet Voting Service, analyzed 10,354 nonpolitical CIVS elections and found cycles in 17% of elections with at least 10 votes, with the figure dropping to 2.1% for elections with at least 100 votes, and 1.2% for ≥300 votes.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Voters' preferences were non-transitive: Arab was preferred over Gordon, Gordon over Wonsley, and Wonsley over Arab, creating a cyclical pattern with no clear winner.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Additionally, the election exhibited a downward monotonicity paradox, as well as a paradox akin to Simpson’s paradox.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] A second instance of a Condorcet cycle was found in the 2022 District 4 School Director election in Oakland, California.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Manigo was preferred to Hutchinson, Hutchinson to Resnick, and Resnick to Manigo.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Like in Minneapolis, the margins were quite narrow: for instance, 11370 voters preferred Manigo to Hutchinson while 11322 preferred Hutchinson to Manigo.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Another instance of a Condorcet cycle was with the seat of Prahran in the 2014 Victorian state election, with a narrow circular tie between the Greens, Liberal, and Labor candidates.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] The Greens candidate, who was initially third on primary votes, defeated the Liberal candidate by less than 300 votes.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] However, if the contest had been between Labor and Liberal, the Liberal candidate would have won by 25 votes.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] While a Greens vs Labor count was not conducted, Liberal preferences tend to flow more towards Labor than Greens in other cases (including in the seat of Richmond in the same election), meaning that Labor would have very likely been preferred to the Greens.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] This means there was a circular pattern, with the Greens preferred over Liberal, who were preferred over Labor, who were preferred over the Greens.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] When a Condorcet method is used to determine an election, the voting paradox of cyclical societal preferences implies that the election has no Condorcet winner: no candidate who can win a one-on-one election against each other candidate.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] There will still be a smallest group of candidates, known as the Smith set, such that each candidate in the group can win a one-on-one election against each of the candidates outside the group.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] The several variants of the Condorcet method differ on how they resolve such ambiguities when they arise to determine a winner.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] The Condorcet methods which always elect someone from the Smith set when there is no Condorcet winner are known as Smith-efficient.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Note that using only rankings, there is no fair and deterministic resolution to the trivial example given earlier because each candidate is in an exactly symmetrical situation.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Situations having the voting paradox can cause voting mechanisms to violate the axiom of independence of irrelevant alternatives—the choice of winner by a voting mechanism could be influenced by whether or not a losing candidate is available to be voted for.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] One important implication of the possible existence of the voting paradox in a practical situation is that in a paired voting process like those of standard parliamentary procedure, the eventual winner will depend on the way the majority votes are ordered.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] For example, say a popular bill is set to pass, before some other group offers an amendment; this amendment passes by majority vote.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] This may result in a majority of a legislature rejecting the bill as a whole, thus creating a paradox (where a popular amendment to a popular bill has made it unpopular).
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] This logical inconsistency is the origin of the poison pill amendment, which deliberately engineers a false Condorcet cycle to kill a bill.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Likewise, the order of votes in a legislature can be manipulated by the person arranging them to ensure their preferred outcome wins.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Condorcet paradoxes imply that majoritarian methods fail independence of irrelevant alternatives.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Label the three candidates in a race *Rock*, *Paper*, and *Scissors*.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] In one-on-one races, Rock loses to Paper, Paper loses to Scissors, and Scissors loses to Rock.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Without loss of generality, say that Rock wins the election with a certain method.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Then, Scissors is a spoiler candidate for Paper; if Scissors were to drop out, Paper would win the only one-on-one race (Paper defeats Rock).
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] The same reasoning applies regardless of the winner.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] This example also shows why Condorcet elections are rarely (if ever) spoiled; spoilers can *only* happen when there is no Condorcet winner.
[src:social-choice-theory/condorcet-paradox] Condorcet cycles are rare in large elections, and the median voter theorem shows that cycles are impossible whenever candidates are arrayed on a left-right spectrum.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] The **Gibbard–Satterthwaite theorem** is a theorem in social choice theory.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] It was first conjectured by the philosopher Michael Dummett and the mathematician Robin Farquharson in 1961 and then proved independently by the philosopher Allan Gibbard in 1973 and economist Mark Satterthwaite in 1975.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] The rule is manipulable, i.e. not strategyproof, i.e., there is no single always-best strategy (one that does not depend on other voters' preferences or behavior).
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Gibbard's proof of the theorem is more general and covers processes of collective decision that may not be ordinal, such as cardinal voting.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Gibbard's 1978 theorem and Hylland's theorem are even more general and extend these results to non-deterministic processes, where the outcome may depend partly on chance; the Duggan–Schwartz theorem extends these results to multiwinner electoral systems.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] The old interpretation views it as a proof that "democracy is impossible", stating that if we require a voting rule to yield a single winner, there are distributions of voter preferences where the rule is dictatorial or "allows manipulation".
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Consider three voters named Alice, Bob and Carol, who wish to select a winner among four candidates named a , b , c and d .
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Assume that they use the Borda count: each voter communicates their preference order over the candidates.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] For each ballot, 3 points are assigned to the top candidate, 2 points to the second candidate, 1 point to the third one and 0 points to the last one.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Once all ballots have been counted, the candidate with the most points is declared the winner.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Assume that their preferences are as follows.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] If the voters cast sincere ballots, then the scores are: $(a:3,b:6,c:7,d:2)$ .
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Hence, candidate c will be elected, with 7 points.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] But Alice can vote strategically and change the result.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Assume that she modifies her ballot, in order to produce the following situation.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Alice has strategically upgraded candidate b and downgraded candidate c .
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Alice is satisfied by her ballot modification, because she prefers the outcome b to c , which is the outcome she would obtain if she voted sincerely.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] We say that the Borda count is *manipulable*: there exists situations where a sincere ballot does not defend a voter's preferences best.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] The Gibbard–Satterthwaite theorem states that every ranked-choice voting is manipulable, except possibly in two cases: if there is a distinguished voter who has a dictatorial power, or if the rule limits the possible outcomes to two options only.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Let ${\mathcal {A}}$ be the set of *alternatives* (which is assumed finite), also called *candidates*, even if they are not necessarily persons: they can also be several possible decisions about a given issue.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Let ${\mathcal {P}}$ be the set of strict weak orders over ${\mathcal {A}}$ : an element of this set can represent the preferences of a voter, where a voter may be indifferent regarding the ordering of some alternatives.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] A *voting rule* is a function $f:{\mathcal {P}}^{n}\to {\mathcal {A}}$ .
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Its input is a profile of preferences $(P_{1},\ldots ,P_{n})\in {\mathcal {P}}^{n}$ and it yields the identity of the winning candidate.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] We say that f is *manipulable* if and only if there exists a profile $(P_{1},\ldots ,P_{n})\in {\mathcal {P}}^{n}$ where some voter i , by replacing her ballot $P_{i}$ with another ballot $P_{i}'$ , can get an outcome that she prefers (in the sense of $P_{i}$ ).
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] We denote by $f({\mathcal {P}}^{n})$ the image of f , i.e. the set of *possible outcomes* for the election.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] For example, we say that f has at least three possible outcomes if and only if the cardinality of $f({\mathcal {P}}^{n})$ is 3 or more.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] We say that f is *dictatorial* if and only if there exists a voter i who is a *dictator*, in the sense that the winning alternative is always her most-liked one among the possible outcomes *regardless of the preferences of other voters*.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] If the dictator has several equally most-liked alternatives among the possible outcomes, then the winning alternative is simply one of them.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] We now consider the case where by assumption, a voter cannot be indifferent between two candidates.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] We denote by ${\mathcal {L}}$ the set of strict total orders over ${\mathcal {A}}$ and we define a *strict voting rule* as a function $f:{\mathcal {L}}^{n}\to {\mathcal {A}}$ .
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] The definitions of *possible outcomes*, *manipulable*, *dictatorial* have natural adaptations to this framework.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] For a strict voting rule, the converse of the Gibbard–Satterthwaite theorem is true.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Indeed, a strict voting rule is dictatorial if and only if it always selects the most-liked candidate of the dictator among the possible outcomes; in particular, it does not depend on the other voters' ballots.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] As a consequence, it is not manipulable: the dictator is perfectly defended by her sincere ballot, and the other voters have no impact on the outcome, hence they have no incentive to deviate from sincere voting.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Thus, we obtain the following equivalence.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] In the theorem, as well as in the corollary, it is not needed to assume that any alternative can be elected.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] It is only assumed that at least three of them can win, i.e. are *possible outcomes* of the voting rule.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] It is possible that some other alternatives can be elected in no circumstances: the theorem and the corollary still apply.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] The assumption of being onto is sometimes even replaced with the assumption that the rule is *unanimous*, in the sense that if all voters prefer the same candidate, then she must be elected.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] The original proofs by Gibbard and Satterthwaite used the Arrow's impossibility theorem for social ranking functions.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] We give a sketch of proof in the simplified case where some voting rule f is assumed to be Pareto-efficient.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] It is possible to build a social ranking function $\operatorname {Rank}$ , as follows: in order to decide whether $a\prec b$ , the $\operatorname {Rank}$ function creates new preferences in which a and b are moved to the top of all voters' preferences.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Then, $\operatorname {Rank}$ examines whether f chooses a or b .
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] It is possible to prove that, if f is non-manipulable and non-dictatorial, $\operatorname {Rank}$ satisfies independence of irrelevant alternatives.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Arrow's impossibility theorem says that, when there are three or more alternatives, such a $\operatorname {Rank}$ function must be a dictatorship.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Hence, such a voting rule f must also be a dictatorship.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Later authors have developed other variants of the proof.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Barbera and Peleg presented a different proof, using the notion of *menus* (also called: *option sets*).
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] For simplicity, we present the proof for *n*=2 voters, and for preferences without ties (The extension to any number of voters can be done by straightforward induction; the extension to preferences with ties is straightforward as long as the domain contains all profiles without ties).
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] For any preference reported by agent 1, the best candidate by that preference is on the menu for agent 2.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Since OPT1 is in range *f*, it equals R(P1*,P2*) for some profile (P1*,P2*).
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] *Proof*: By Lemma 2, x is in both Menu2(P1) and Menu2(P1*).
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] If the menus are not equal, then (wlog) some candidate z is in Menu2(P1) and not in Menu2(P1*).
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Let P2* be a preference that ranks z first, x second, and then all other candidates.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] But this means that x is in Menu1(P2), so by Lemma 1 again, *f*(P1,P2*) = Best(P1, Menu1(P2*))=*x* --- a contradiction [agent 1 could manipulate from P1 to P1*].
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] For every x and z in Range(f), and for every Px with best candidate x and Pz with best candidate z, **Px prefers Best(Pz,Menu2(x)) to z**.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] *Proof*: Take x,z,Px,Pz as in the lemma statement, and let y=Best(Pz,Menu2(x)).
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Assume by contradiction that Px prefers z to y.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] But this means that z is in Menu1(Pz), so y cannot be Best(Px, Menu1(Pz)).
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] But by Lemma 1, *f*(Px,Pz) = Best(Px, Menu1(Pz)) --- a contradiction [agent 1 can profitably manipulate from Px to Pz].
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] For every x in Range(f), Menu2(x) is either a singleton or the entire Range(f).
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] *Proof*: By contradiction, let x be some candidate that violates that statement.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] So Menu2(x) contains x (by Lemma 2), and some other element y (as it is not a singleton), but not some third element z (as it is not the entire range).
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Then there is a preference Px with best candidate x, that prefers z to y; and a preference Pz with best candidate z, that ranks y second.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Then Best(Pz, Menu2(x)) = y but Px prefers z to y, contradicting Lemma 5.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Menu2(x) is either a singleton for all x, or the entire Range(*f*) for all x.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] *Proof*: By contradiction, let x be some candidate for which Menu2(x) is a singleton (and must be equal to {x}), and y some other candidate for which Menu2(y) = Range(*f*).
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Let Py be a preference with best element y, that prefers x to some third candidate z (here we assume that Range(f) contains at least three candidates).
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Since Menu2(Py) = Range(*f*), there is some P2 for which f(Py,P2)=z.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] But then agent 1 could manipulate from Py to some preference Px with best element x, as this would force the outcome to be x.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Gibbard's theorem deals with processes of collective choice that may not be ordinal, i.e. where a voter's action may not consist in communicating a preference order over the candidates.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Gibbard's 1978 theorem and Hylland's theorem extend these results to non-deterministic mechanisms, i.e. where the outcome may not only depend on the ballots but may also involve a part of chance.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] The Duggan–Schwartz theorem extend this result in another direction, by dealing with deterministic voting rules that choose multiple winners.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] The GS theorem crucially relies on the fact that *all* preference rankings over the sets of candidates are possible.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] The theorem might not hold under *domain restrictions*, that is, when the agents are allowed to express preferences from a restricted set.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] There are various works studying possibility and impossibility results for restricted preference domains.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] When the agents are restricted to have single-peaked preferences, the GS theorem does not hold, as the median voting rule is strategyproof and non-dictatorial.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Barbera and Peleg consider voting on continuous domains, such as budget-proposal aggregation, when the set of candidates is some metric space *M*, and the agents' preferences are restricted to continuous utility functions over *M*.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] They extend their Proof by Menus (above) to this restricted domain.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] As a preliminary result, they prove that it is sufficient to consider preferences with a *single* best candidate.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] They prove that, if a voting rule *f* is dictatorial when restricted to preferences with a single best candidate, then it remains dictatorial without that restriction.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] They also prove that this restriction does not change the range of *f*.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] They also prove that Range(*f*) is a closed set, and that for every utility continuous function u1, Menu2(u1) is a closed set.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Let u2z be the following continuous utility function: u2z(y) = ${\frac {d(y,M\setminus Ball(z,r))}{d(y,z)+d(y,M\setminus Ball(z,r))}}$ , where *M* is the set of all candidates, and *d* is its metric.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] This function looks like a dome with a peak at z; it has u2z(t)=0 for all *t* in Menu2(u1*), and z = Best(u2z).
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Similarly, let u2x be the following continuous utility function: u2x(y) = ${\frac {d(y,M\setminus Ball(x,r))}{2[d(y,x)+d(y,M\setminus Ball(x,r))]}}$ ; it is a dome with a peak at x.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Note that Ball(z,r) and Ball(x,r) do not intersect.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Finally, let u2* := u2z+u2x; it has a high dome with a peak at z, and a distinct lower dome with a peak at x.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Simultaneously, f(u1*,u2*) = Best(u2*,Menu2(u1*)) = x, as the entire dome with peak at z is not in Menu2(u1*).
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Hence, when 2 reports u2*, agent 1 can gain by manipulating from u1 to u1*.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Hence, we can still write the menu as a function of the best element: Menu2(*x*) = Menu2(u1) for all u1 with best element x.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] The rest of the proof is similar to the finite case: Lemma 6 implies Lemma 7, which implies that either agent 1 or agent 2 is a dictator.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] The strategic aspect of voting is already noticed in 1876 by Charles Dodgson, also known as Lewis Carroll, a pioneer in social choice theory.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] During the 1950s, Robin Farquharson published influential articles on voting theory.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] In an article with Michael Dummett, he conjectures that deterministic voting rules with at least three outcomes are never straightforward tactical voting.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] This conjecture was later proven independently by Allan Gibbard and Mark Satterthwaite.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] In a 1973 article, Gibbard exploits Arrow's impossibility theorem from 1951 to prove the result we now know as Gibbard's theorem.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] Independently, Satterthwaite proved the same result in his PhD dissertation in 1973, then published it in a 1975 article.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] This proof is also based on Arrow's impossibility theorem, but does not involve the more general version given by Gibbard's theorem.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] The Gibbard–Satterthwaite theorem is generally presented as a result about voting systems, but it can also be seen as an important result of mechanism design, which deals with a broader class of decision rules.
[src:social-choice-theory/gibbard-satterthwaite-theorem] The main idea of these "escape routes" is that they allow for a broader class of mechanisms than ranked voting, similarly to the escape routes from Arrow's impossibility theorem.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Real-world examples of social choice rules include constitutions and parliamentary procedures for voting on laws, as well as electoral systems; as such, the field is occasionally called **voting theory**.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] It is closely related to mechanism design, which uses game theory to model social choice with imperfect information and self-interested citizens.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Social choice differs from decision theory in that the latter is concerned with how *individuals*, rather than *societies*, can make rational decisions.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] The earliest work on social choice theory comes from the writings of the Marquis de Condorcet, who formulated several key results including his jury theorem and his example showing the impossibility of majority rule.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] His work was prefigured by Ramon Llull's 1299 manuscript *Ars Electionis* (*The Art of Elections*), which discussed many of the same concepts, but was lost in the Late Middle Ages and only rediscovered in the early 21st century.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Kenneth Arrow's book *Social Choice and Individual Values* is often recognized as inaugurating the modern era of social choice theory.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Later work has also considered approaches to legal compensation, fair division, variable populations, partial strategy-proofing of social-choice mechanisms, natural resources, capabilities and functionings approaches, and measures of welfare.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Arrow's impossibility theorem is a key result showing that social choice functions based only on ordinal comparisons, rather than cardinal utility, will behave incoherently (unless they are dictatorial).
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Such systems violate independence of irrelevant alternatives, meaning they suffer from spoiler effects—the system can behave erratically in response to changes in the quality or popularity of one of the options.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Condorcet's example demonstrates that democracy cannot be thought of as being the same as simple majority rule or majoritarianism; otherwise, it will be self-contradictory when three or more options are available.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Majority rule can create cycles that violate the transitive property: Attempting to use majority rule as a social choice function creates situations where we have A better than B and B better than C, but C is also better than A.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] This contrasts with May's theorem, which shows that simple majority is the optimal voting mechanism when there are only two outcomes, and only ordinal preferences are allowed.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Harsanyi's utilitarian theorem shows that if individuals have preferences that are well-behaved under uncertainty (i.e. coherent), the only coherent and Pareto efficient social choice function is the utilitarian rule.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] This lends some support to the viewpoint expressed of John Stuart Mill, who identified democracy with the ideal of maximizing the common good (or utility) of society as a whole, under an equal consideration of interests.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Gibbard's theorem provides limitations on the ability of any voting rule to elicit honest preferences from voters, showing that no voting rule is strategyproof (i.e. does not depend on other voters' preferences) for elections with 3 or more outcomes.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] The Gibbard–Satterthwaite theorem proves a stronger result for ranked-choice voting systems, showing that no such voting rule can be sincere (i.e. free of reversed preferences).
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] The field of mechanism design, a subset of social choice theory, deals with the identification of rules that preserve while incentivizing agents to honestly reveal their preferences.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] One particularly important result is the revelation principle, which is almost a reversal of Gibbard's theorem: for any given social choice function, there exists a mechanism that obtains the same results but incentivizes participants to be completely honest.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Because mechanism design places stronger assumptions on the behavior of participants, it is sometimes possible to design mechanisms for social choice that accomplish apparently-"impossible" tasks.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] For example, by allowing agents to compensate each other for losses with transfers, the Vickrey–Clarke–Groves (VCG) mechanism can achieve the "impossible" according to Gibbard's theorem: the mechanism ensures honest behavior from participants, while still achieving a Pareto efficient outcome.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] As a result, the VCG mechanism can be considered a "better" way to make decisions than voting (though only so long as monetary transfers are possible).
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] 19 years after Arrow’s *Social Choice and Individual Values* was published, in 1970, Sen would publish *Collective Choice and Social Welfare*, which "expanded Arrow’s original social choice framework".
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] In it, Sen outlines several “conditions” that would likely produce a balanced, satisfactory outcome for both the majority and individual members of society.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Whereas Arrow had penned his theorem with the assumption of ordinality, Sen introduced the assumption of cardinality, or interpersonal comparison, into the social-choice theory model.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] The problem with ordinality is that it excludes "information about each individual’s strength of preference or about how to compare different individuals' preferences with one another".
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] In contrast, Sen’s version of social-choice theory notes the importance of taking into consideration factors like equality of opportunity and “capability” as they relate to individual preferences.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Sen replaced utilitarian welfare economics’ “individual utility” with the concept of “capability,” which can be defined as a person’s freedom of choice and economic mobility in a society.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Furthermore, Sen emphasized that the preferences of the poor should “be the decisive criterion” in deciding an outcome.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] If the domain of preferences is restricted to those that include a majority-strength Condorcet winner, then selecting that winner is the unique resolvable, neutral, anonymous, and non-manipulable voting rule.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Social choice theory is the study of theoretical and practical methods to aggregate or combine individual preferences into a collective social welfare function.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] The field generally assumes that individuals have preferences, and it follows that they can be modeled using utility functions, by the VNM theorem.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] But much of the research in the field assumes that those utility functions are internal to humans, lack a meaningful unit of measure and *cannot* be compared across different individuals.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Whether this type of *interpersonal utility comparison* is possible or not significantly alters the available mathematical structures for social welfare functions and social choice theory.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] In one perspective, following Jeremy Bentham, utilitarians have argued that preferences and utility functions of individuals are interpersonally comparable and may therefore be added together to arrive at a measure of aggregate utility.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Utilitarian ethics call for maximizing this aggregate.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] In contrast many twentieth century economists, following Lionel Robbins, questioned whether such measures of utility could be measured, or even considered meaningful.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Following arguments similar to those espoused by behaviorists in psychology, Robbins argued concepts of utility were unscientific and unfalsifiable.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Consider for instance the law of diminishing marginal utility, according to which utility of an added quantity of a good decreases with the amount of the good that is already in possession of the individual.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] It has been used to defend transfers of wealth from the "rich" to the "poor" on the premise that the former do not derive as much utility as the latter from an extra unit of income.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Robbins argued that this notion is beyond positive science; that is, one cannot measure changes in the utility of someone else, nor is it required by positive theory.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Apologists for the interpersonal comparison of utility have argued that Robbins claimed too much.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] John Harsanyi agreed that perfect comparisons of mental states are not practically possible, but people can still make *some* comparisons thanks to their similar backgrounds, cultural experiences, and psychologies.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Amartya Sen argues that even if interpersonal comparisons of utility are imperfect, we can still say that (despite being positive for Nero) the Great Fire of Rome had a negative overall value.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Harsanyi and Sen thus argue that at least *partial* comparability of utility is possible, and social choice theory should proceed under that assumption.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Despite the similar names, "public choice" and "social choice" are two distinct fields that are only weakly related.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Public choice deals with the modeling of political systems as they actually exist in the real world, and is primarily limited to positive economics (predicting how politicians and other stakeholders will act).
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] It is therefore often thought of as the application of microeconomic models to political science, in order to predict the behavior of political actors.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] By contrast, social choice has a much more normative bent, and deals with the abstract study of decision procedures and their properties.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] The Journal of Economic Literature classification codes place Social Choice under Microeconomics at JEL D71 (with Clubs, Committees, and Associations) whereas Public Choice falls under JEL D72 (Economic Models of Political Processes: Rent-Seeking, Elections, Legislatures, and Voting Behavior).
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Since Arrow, social choice theory has been characterized by being predominantly mathematical and theoretical, but some research has aimed at estimating the frequency of various voting paradoxes, such as the Condorcet paradox.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] A summary of 37 individual studies, covering a total of 265 real-world elections, large and small, found 25 instances of a Condorcet paradox for a total likelihood of 9.4%.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] While examples of the paradox seem to occur often in small settings like parliaments, very few examples have been found in larger groups (electorates), although some have been identified.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] However, the frequency of such paradoxes depends heavily on the number of options and other factors.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Let X be a set of possible 'states of the world' or 'alternatives'.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Society wishes to choose a single state from X .
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] For example, in a single-winner election, X may represent the set of candidates; in a resource allocation setting, X may represent all possible allocations.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Let I be a finite set, representing a collection of individuals.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] For each $i\in I$ , let $u_{i}:X\longrightarrow \mathbb {R}$ be a *utility function*, describing the amount of happiness an individual *i* derives from each possible state.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] A *social choice rule* is a mechanism which uses the data $(u_{i})_{i\in I}$ to select some element(s) from X which are 'best' for society.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] The question of what 'best' means is a common question in social choice theory.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] A social choice function, sometimes called a voting system in the context of politics, is a rule that takes an individual's complete and transitive preferences over a set of outcomes and returns a single chosen outcome (or a set of tied outcomes).
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] We can think of this subset as the winners of an election, and compare different social choice functions based on which axioms or mathematical properties they fulfill.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] Arrow's impossibility theorem is what often comes to mind when one thinks about impossibility theorems in voting.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] There are several famous theorems concerning social choice functions.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] The Gibbard–Satterthwaite theorem implies that the only rule satisfying non-imposition (every alternative can be chosen) and strategyproofness when there are more than two candidates is the dictatorship mechanism.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] That is, a voter may be able to cast a ballot that misrepresents their preferences to obtain a result that is more favorable to them under their sincere preferences.
[src:social-choice-theory/social-choice-theory] May's theorem shows that when there are only two candidates and only rankings of options are available, the simple majority vote is the unique neutral, anonymous, and positively-responsive voting rule.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] A Condorcet winner (French: [kɔ̃dɔʁsɛ], English: /kɒndɔːrˈseɪ/) is a candidate who would receive more support than their opponent in a one-on-one race against any one of their opponents.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Voting systems where a Condorcet winner will always win the election are said to satisfy the Condorcet winner criterion.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The Condorcet winner criterion extends the principle of majority rule to elections with multiple candidates.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Named after Nicolas de Condorcet, it is also called a majority winner, a majority-preferred candidate, a beats-all winner, or tournament winner (by analogy with round-robin tournaments).
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] A Condorcet winner may not necessarily always exist in a given electorate: for example, it is possible to have a rock paper scissors-style cycle, when multiple candidates defeat each other (rock < paper < scissors < rock).
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] This is called Condorcet's voting paradox, and is analogous to the counterintuitive intransitive dice phenomenon known in probability.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] However, the Smith set, a generalization of the Condorcet criteria that is the smallest set of candidates that are pairwise unbeaten by every candidate outside of it, will always exist.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] However, political electorates are inherently multidimensional in real-life, and the use of a one- or even two-dimensional model of such electorates would be inaccurate.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] For multi-dimensional spaces there might be no Condorcet winner according to the McKelvey–Schofield chaos theorem.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Previous research has found cycles to be somewhat rare in real elections, with estimates of their prevalence ranging from 1% to 10% of races.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Systems that guarantee the election of a Condorcet winners (when one exists) include Ranked pairs, Schulze's method, and the Tideman alternative method.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Methods that do *not* guarantee that the Cordorcet winner will be elected, even when one does exist, include instant-runoff voting (often called ranked-choice in the United States), first-past-the-post voting, and the two-round system.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Most rated systems (like score voting and the highest median rules) are not Condorcet methods, as they try to account for the strengths of different voters' preferences rather than always following the majority.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] In single-winner voting system theory, the Condorcet loser criterion (CLC) is a measure for differentiating voting systems.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] It implies the majority loser criterion but does not imply the Condorcet winner criterion.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] A voting system complying with the Condorcet loser criterion will never allow a *Condorcet loser* to win.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] A Condorcet loser is a candidate who can be defeated in a head-to-head competition against each other candidate.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The Smith set, sometimes called the top-cycle generalizes the idea of a Condorcet winner to cases where no such winner exists.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] It does so by allowing cycles of candidates to be treated jointly, as if they were a single Condorcet winner.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Voting systems that always elect a candidate from the Smith set pass the Smith criterion.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The Smith set and Smith criterion are both named for mathematician John H.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The Smith set provides one standard of optimal choice for an election outcome.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] An alternative, stricter criterion is given by the Landau set.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] A voting system satisfies join-consistency (also called the reinforcement criterion) if combining two sets of votes, both electing *A* over *B*, always results in a combined electorate that ranks *A* over *B*.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] It is a stronger form of the participation criterion.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Systems that fail the consistency criterion (such as instant-runoff voting or Condorcet methods) are susceptible to the multiple-district paradox, a pathological behavior where a candidate can win an election without carrying even a single precinct.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Conversely, it can be seen as allowing for a particularly egregious kind of gerrymander: it is possible to draw boundaries in such a way that a candidate who wins the overall election fails to carry even a single electoral district.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Rules susceptible to the multiple-districts paradox include all Condorcet methods and instant-runoff (or ranked-choice) voting.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Rules that are not susceptible to it include all positional voting rules (such as first-preference plurality and the Borda count) as well as score voting and approval voting.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Homogeneity is a common property for voting systems.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The property is satisfied if, in any election, the result depends only on the proportion of ballots of each possible type.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] That is, if every ballot is replicated the same number of times, then the result should not change.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Independence of irrelevant alternatives (IIA) is an axiom of decision theory which codifies the intuition that a choice between A and B (which are both related) should not depend on the quality of a third, unrelated outcome ${\textstyle C}$ .
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] There are several different variations of this axiom, which are generally equivalent under mild conditions.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] As a result of its importance, the axiom has been independently rediscovered in various forms across a wide variety of fields, including economics, cognitive science, social choice, fair division, rational choice, artificial intelligence, probability, and game theory.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] It is closely tied to many of the most important theorems in these fields, including Arrow's impossibility theorem, the Balinski–Young theorem, and the money pump arguments.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] In behavioral economics, failures of IIA (caused by irrationality) are called menu effects or menu dependence.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] In social choice theory, the independence of (irrelevant) clones criterion says that adding a *clone*, i.e. a new candidate very similar to an already-existing candidate, should not spoil the results.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] It can be considered a weak form of the independence of irrelevant alternatives (IIA) criterion that nevertheless is failed by a number of voting rules.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] A method that passes the criterion is said to be clone independent.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] A group of candidates are called clones if they are always ranked together, placed side-by-side, by every voter; no voter ranks any of the non-clone candidates between or equal to the clones.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] In other words, the process of *cloning* a candidate involves taking an existing candidate *C*, then replacing them with several candidates *C1*, *C2..*. who are slotted into the original ballots in the spot where *C* previously was, with the clones being arranged in any order.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] If a set of clones contains at least two candidates, the criterion requires that deleting one of the clones must not increase or decrease the winning chance of any candidate not in the set of clones.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Ranked pairs, the Schulze method, and systems that unconditionally satisfy independence of irrelevant alternatives are clone independent.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Instant-runoff voting passes as long as tied ranks are disallowed.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] If they are allowed, its clone independence depends on specific details of how the criterion is defined and how tied ranks are handled.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Rated methods like range voting or majority judgment that are spoilerproof under certain conditions are also clone independent under those conditions.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The Borda count, minimax, Kemeny–Young, Copeland's method, plurality, and the two-round system all fail the independence of clones criterion.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Voting methods that limit the number of allowed ranks also fail the criterion, because the addition of clones can leave voters with insufficient space to express their preferences about other candidates.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] For similar reasons, ballot formats that impose such a limit may cause an otherwise clone-independent method to fail.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] This criterion is very weak, as adding a substantially similar (but not quite identical) candidate to a race can still substantially affect the results and cause vote splitting.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] For example, the center squeeze pathology that affects instant-runoff voting means that several similar (but not identical) candidates competing in the same race will tend to hurt each other's chances of winning.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Independence of Smith-dominated alternatives (ISDA, also known as Smith-IIA) is a voting system criterion which says that the winner of an election should not be affected by candidates who are not in the Smith set.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Another way of defining ISDA is to say that adding a new candidate should not change the winner of an election, *unless* that new candidate would beat the original winner, either directly or indirectly.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Later-no-harm is a property of voting systems first described by Douglas Woodall.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] In later-no-harm systems, increasing the rating or rank of a candidate ranked below the winner of an election cannot cause a higher-ranked candidate to lose.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] It is a common property in the plurality-rule family of voting systems.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] For example, say a group of voters ranks Alice 2nd and Bob 6th, and Alice wins the election.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] In the next election, Bob focuses on expanding his appeal with this group of voters, but does not manage to defeat Alice—Bob's rating increases from 6th-place to 3rd.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Later-no-harm says that this increased support from Alice's voters should not allow Bob to win.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Later-no-harm may be confused as implying center squeeze, since later-no-harm is a defining characteristic of first-preference plurality (FPP) and instant-runoff voting (IRV), and descending solid coalitions (DSC), systems that have similar mechanics that are based on first preference counting.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] These systems pass later-no-harm compliance by making sure the results either do not depend on lower preferences at all (plurality) or only depend on them if all higher preferences have been eliminated (IRV and DSC), and thus exhibit a center squeeze effect.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] However, this does not mean that methods that pass later-no-harm must be vulnerable to center squeezes.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The properties are distinct, as Minimax opposition also passes later-no-harm.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Later-no-harm is also often confused with immunity to a kind of strategic voting called strategic truncation or bullet voting.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Satisfying later-no-harm does not provide immunity to such strategies.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Systems like instant runoff that pass later-no-harm but fail monotonicity still incentivize truncation or bullet voting in some situations.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The later-no-help criterion (or LNHe, not to be confused with LNH) is a voting system criterion formulated by Douglas Woodall.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The criterion is satisfied if, in any election, a voter giving an additional ranking or positive rating to a less-preferred candidate can not cause a more-preferred candidate to win.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Voting systems that fail the later-no-help criterion are vulnerable to the tactical voting strategy called mischief voting, which can deny victory to a sincere Condorcet winner.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The majority criterion is a voting system criterion applicable to voting rules over ordinal preferences required that if only one candidate is ranked first by over 50% of voters, that candidate must win.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Some methods that comply with this criterion include any Condorcet method, instant-runoff voting, Bucklin voting, plurality voting, and approval voting.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The majority loser criterion is a criterion to evaluate single-winner voting systems.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The criterion states that if a majority of voters give a candidate no support, i.e. do not list that candidate on their ballot, that candidate must lose (unless no candidate is accepted by a majority of voters).
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Either of the Condorcet loser criterion or the mutual majority criterion implies the majority loser criterion.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] However, the Condorcet criterion does not imply the majority loser criterion, since the minimax method satisfies the Condorcet but not the majority loser criterion.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Also, the majority criterion is logically independent from the majority loser criterion, since the plurality rule satisfies the majority but not the majority loser criterion, and the anti-plurality rule satisfies the majority loser but not the majority criterion.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] There is no positional scoring rule which satisfies both the majority and the majority loser criterion, but several non-positional rules, including many Condorcet rules, do satisfy both.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Some voting systems, like instant-runoff voting, fail the criterion if extended to handle incomplete ballots.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Non-negative responsiveness or monotonicity is a property of a social choice rule, which says that increasing a candidate's rank on some ballots should not cause them to lose (or vice versa, that decreasing a candidate's rank should not cause them to win).
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] This means rankings can be interpreted as ordering candidates from best to worst, with higher ranks corresponding to more support.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Voting systems that violate non-negative responsiveness can be said to exhibit negative response, perversity, or an additional support paradox.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Perversity is often described by social choice theorists as an exceptionally severe kind of electoral pathology, as such rules can have "backwards" responses to voters' opinions, where popularity causes defeat while unpopularity leads to a win.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Such rules treat the well-being of some voters as "less than worthless".
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] These issues have led to constitutional prohibitions on such systems as violating the right to equal and direct suffrage.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Negative response is often cited as an example of a perverse incentive, as rules with negative response can incentivize politicians to take extreme or unpopular positions in an attempt to shed excess votes.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Most ranked methods (including Borda and all common round-robin rules) satisfy non-negative responsiveness, as do all common rated voting methods (including approval, highest medians, and score).
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Negative responsiveness occurs in instant-runoff voting (IRV), the single transferable vote, and the two-round system.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Some quota-based apportionment methods also violate the rule, as can the randomized Condorcet method in cases of cyclic ties.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The participation criterion is closely related, but different.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] While non-negative responsiveness deals with a voter changing their opinion (or vote), participation deals with situations where a voter choosing to cast a ballot at all has a backwards effect on the election.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Proportionality for solid coalitions (PSC) is a criterion of proportionality for ranked voting systems.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] It is an adaptation of the quota rule to voting systems in which there are no official party lists, and voters can directly support candidates.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The criterion was first proposed by the British philosopher and logician Michael Dummett.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] PSC is a relatively minimal definition of proportionality.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] To be guaranteed representation, a coalition of voters must rank all candidates within the same party first before candidates of other parties.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] And PSC does not guarantee proportional representation if voters rank candidates of different parties together (as they will no longer form a solid coalition).
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The participation criterion is a voting system criterion that says candidates should never lose an election as a result of receiving too many votes in support.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] More formally, it says that adding more voters who prefer *Alice* to *Bob* should not cause *Alice* to lose the election to *Bob*.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Positional methods and score voting satisfy the participation criterion.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] All deterministic voting rules that satisfy pairwise majority-rule can fail in situations involving four-way cyclic ties, though such scenarios are empirically rare, and the randomized Condorcet rule is not affected by the pathology.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The majority judgment rule fails as well.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Instant-runoff voting and the two-round system both fail the participation criterion with high frequency in competitive elections, typically as a result of a center squeeze.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The no-show paradox is similar to, but not the same as, the perverse response paradox.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Perverse response happens when an *existing* voter can make a candidate win by *de*creasing their rating of that candidate (or vice-versa).
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] For example, under instant-runoff voting, moving a candidate from first-place to last-place on a ballot can cause them to win.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] If the number of ballots ranking A as the first preference is greater than the number of ballots on which another candidate B is given any preference [other than last], then A's probability of winning must be no less than B's.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Among Condorcet methods which permit truncation, whether the plurality criterion is satisfied depends often on the measure of defeat strength.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] When *winning votes* is used as the measure of defeat strength, plurality is satisfied.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Plurality is failed when *margins* is used.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Minimax using *pairwise opposition* also fails plurality.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] When truncation is permitted under Borda count, the plurality criterion is satisfied when no points are scored to truncated candidates, and ranked candidates receive no fewer votes than if the truncated candidates had been ranked.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] If truncated candidates are instead scored the average number of points that would have been awarded to those candidates had they been strictly ranked, or if Nauru's modified Borda count is used, the plurality criterion is failed.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] A voting system is called decisive, resolvable, or resolute if it ensures a low probability of tied elections.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] There are two different criterion that formalize this.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] A non-resolvable social choice function is often only considered to be a *partial* electoral method, sometimes called a voting correspondence or set-valued voting rule.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Such methods frequently require tiebreakers that can substantially affect the result.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] However, non-resolute methods can be used as a first stage to eliminate candidates before ties are broken with some other method.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Methods that have been used this way include the Copeland set, the Smith set, and the Landau set.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] In other words, the results of the election should not depend arbitrarily on whether voters rank candidates from best to worst (and then select the best candidate), or whether we ask them to rank candidates from worst to best (and then select the least-bad candidate).
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Another, equivalent way to motivate the criterion is to say that a voting system should never elect the worst candidate, according to the method itself (as doing so suggests the method is, in some sense, self-contradictory).
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] The worst candidate can be identified by reversing all ballots (to rank candidates from worst-to-best) and then running the algorithm to find a single worst candidate.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Situations where the same candidate is elected when all ballots are reversed are sometimes called best-is-worst paradoxes, and can occur in instant-runoff voting and minimax.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Methods that satisfy reversal symmetry include the Borda count, ranked pairs, Kemeny–Young, and Schulze.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Most rated voting systems, including approval and score voting, satisfy the criterion as well.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] In social choice theory, unrestricted domain, or universality, is a property of social welfare functions in which all preferences of all voters (but no other considerations) are allowed.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Intuitively, unrestricted domain is a common requirement for social choice functions, and is a condition for Arrow's impossibility theorem.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] With unrestricted domain, the social welfare function accounts for all preferences among all voters to yield a unique and complete ranking of societal choices.
[src:social-choice-theory/voting-criteria] Thus, the voting mechanism must account for all individual preferences, it must do so in a manner that results in a complete ranking of preferences for society, and it must deterministically provide the same ranking each time voters' preferences are presented the same way.
